The `debounce` function ensures that a specified function is not called until a certain amount of time has passed since the last call, thus optimizing performance by avoiding unnecessary executions during rapid events like scrolling or typing.

```javascript
function debounce(func, wait) {
    let timeout;
    return function(...args) {
        clearTimeout(timeout);
        timeout = setTimeout(() => func.apply(this, args), wait);
    };
}

// Example usage:

// A function that logs the input value
function logInput() {
    const value = document.getElementById('input').value;
    console.log('Input value:', value);
}

// Debounced version of the logInput function with a 300ms delay
const debouncedLogInput = debounce(logInput, 300);

// Attach the debounced function to an input field's input event
document.getElementById('input').addEventListener('input', debouncedLogInput);
```

In this example, `debounce` is used to limit how often `logInput` is called when typing in an input field. The function will only execute 300 milliseconds after the user stops typing, reducing unnecessary calls and improving performance.
